│ THOUGHT: Now I need to understand the specific issue better. The problem is │
│ that the SLP vectorizer is trying to vectorize operations that involve both │
│ sign-extended and zero-extended values, but it's not preserving the correct │
│ semantics. Looking at the original IR, we have:                             │
│                                                                             │
│ 1. `%conv7.i84.peel.i = sext i16 0 to i32` (sign extension of 0 → 0)        │
│ 2. `%xor5.i81.peel.i = zext i16 %sub.i.i79.peel.i to i32` (zero extension   │
│ of -1 → 65535)                                                              │
│                                                                             │
│ When comparing these as i32 values: `icmp slt i32 0, 65535` → true          │
│                                                                             │
│ But in the vectorized version, it's creating:                               │
│ - `<2 x i16> zeroinitializer` which is `<0, 0>`                             │
│ - `%0 = insertelement <2 x i16> <poison, 0>, i16 %sub.i.i79.peel.i, i32 0`  │
│ which is `<-1, 0>`                                                          │
│                                                                             │
│ Then doing: `icmp slt <2 x i16> <0, 0>, <-1, 0>` which gives `<false,       │
│ false>` because as signed 16-bit integers, 0 is not less than -1.           │
│                                                                             │
│ The core issue is that the vectorizer is incorrectly assuming that it can   │
